Moroccan journalist Hajar Raissouni was sentenced in a Rabat court Monday to one year in jail for having had an “illegal abortion” and sexual relations outside marriage.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

Her gynaecologist was given two years and her Sudanese fiance one year in prison, while an anaesthetist was handed a one-year suspended sentence and a medical assistant eight months, also suspended.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

Lawyers for 28-year-old Raissouni had called for her acquittal during the trial, denying she had had an abortion.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

“This trial had no foundation – the accusations were baseless,” said defence lawyer Abdelmoula El Marouri after the verdict.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

A journalist for Akhbar Al-Yaoum – an Arabic-language newspaper which has a history of run-ins with the authorities – Raissouni was sentenced under Article 490 of the legal code of the Muslim kingdom.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

That article punishes sexual relations out of wedlock, while the law also forbids all abortions unless the mother’s life is in danger.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

Meriem Moulay Rachid, lawyer for the convicted gynaecologist, said: “The judicial system has had its word, (but) we will appeal.”<\/p>\r\n\r\n

Relatives of Raissouni also told AFP that they would appeal.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

Raissouni had appeared serene when arriving at the courtroom, wearing a black veil covering her head.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

She waved to her relatives before taking her place in the dock.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

