Raissouni was arrested on August 31 as she left a clinic in Rabat.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

In court, she denied having had an abortion and said she had been treated for internal bleeding – testimony backed up by her gynaecologist.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

The journalist denounced a “political trial”, saying she had been questioned by police about her family – including an uncle who is an outspoken Islamist newspaper columnist – and about her own writing.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

The prosecution insisted she had been seen by a medic and showed signs of pregnancy and of having undergone a “late voluntary abortion”.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

It had contended her detention had “nothing to do with her profession as a journalist”.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

The reporter herself said she had been “forced into a medical examination without her consent”.<\/p>\r\n\r\n

